## Architecture Non-Negotiables (Article VII.3)

### 5-Crate Hexagonal Workspace

```
backend/
├── Cargo.toml              ← workspace manifest (overlay, see ADR-002)
├── rust-toolchain.toml     ← stable channel pin
├── crates/
│   ├── domain/             ← pure Rust: entities, value objects, domain events
│   ├── application/        ← use cases, port traits, no infra imports
│   ├── grpc-api/           ← tonic adapter; consumes shared/protos/ via tonic-build
│   └── infrastructure/     ← sqlx (postgres), reqwest (HTTP), message broker clients
└── bin-server/             ← main() wires DI; zero business logic
```

### Strict Dependency Rules

- `crates/domain/` is **pure Rust** — zero dependency on tonic, sqlx, reqwest,
  or any I/O crate. Domain errors use `thiserror`. No async in domain structs.
- `crates/application/` depends on `crates/domain/` only. It defines **port
  traits** (e.g. `UserRepository`, `EmailSender`) that infrastructure adapters
  implement. No direct infra imports.
- `crates/grpc-api/` is an adapter layer. It uses `tonic-build` (in
  `build.rs`) to compile `.proto` files from `../shared/protos/` and maps
  gRPC requests/responses to application types.
- `crates/infrastructure/` provides adapter implementations of the ports
  declared in `application/`. It may import sqlx, reqwest, lapin/rdkafka, etc.
- `bin-server/` contains **only** `main()`, DI wiring, and server startup.
  No business logic allowed here. `anyhow::Result` is acceptable at this layer.

### No Panics in Production Code

`unwrap()` and `panic!()` are **forbidden** in production code paths
(`src/` files outside `#[cfg(test)]` blocks). This is enforced by
`.forge/scripts/verify.sh`. Use `?` propagation and typed errors instead.

Acceptable exceptions (must be justified in a code comment):
- `const` expressions that can only fail at compile time.
- Test code inside `#[cfg(test)]` or `tests/` directories.

